{"id":"quant-ph/0002037","submitter":"Apoorva D. Patel","authors":"Apoorva Patel (CTS and SERC, IISc, Bangalore)","title":"Quantum Algorithms and the Genetic Code","comments":"Revtex, 11 pages, 3 figures. Invited lectures presented at the Winter\n  Institute on ``Foundations of Quantum Theory and Quantum Optics'', 1-13\n  January 2000, S.N. Bose National Centre for Basic Sciences, Calcutta, India.\n  To appear in the proceedings. (v2) Corrected typo in Fig.2 caption. (v3)\n  Published version. Corrected typos and added some comments about enzymes","journal-ref":"Pramana 56 (2001) 365","doi":"10.1007/s12043-001-0131-8","report-no":"IISc-CTS-2/00","categories":"quant-ph cond-mat hep-th physics.bio-ph q-bio.GN","license":null,"abstract":"  Replication of DNA and synthesis of proteins are studied from the view-point\nof quantum database search. Identification of a base-pairing with a quantum\nquery gives a natural (and first ever) explanation of why living organisms have\n4 nucleotide bases and 20 amino acids. It is amazing that these numbers arise\nas solutions to an optimisation problem. Components of the DNA structure which\nimplement Grover's algorithm are identified, and a physical scenario is\npresented for the execution of the quantum algorithm. It is proposed that\nenzymes play a crucial role in maintaining quantum coherence of the process.\nExperimental tests that can verify this scenario are pointed out.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 14 Feb 2000 15:55:22 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Tue, 15 Feb 2000 13:50:28 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Tue, 6 Feb 2001 07:42:09 GMT"}],"update_date":"2009-11-06"}
